description: Apparently a corruption of Latin valdē bona (“very good”) (a plant mentioned in Leonhart Fuchs's Great Herbal). Earliest forms seem to come from an intermediate, unattested French form baudemoine (modern French baudremoine) and by analogy to the plant name agrimony.

entries.meaning: Meum athamanticum, an ornamental plant in the Apiaceae family.
examples: Synonyms: meu, meon, meum, spignel, bearwort

entries.meaning: (obsolete) A Gentianeae tribe plant, gentian or felwort.
